# Inline help tooltips

Form fields whose meaning, units, or sensible default isn't obvious
from the label alone get an inline help icon. The icon opens a Radix
tooltip carrying long-form prose — explanation, defaults, recommended
values, and caveats. Curators don't have to read external docs for
the common case; the answer is one keypress away.

## Use it for

- **Numeric knobs with non-obvious units** (`num_ctx`, `timeout_ms`,
  `error_window_size`): explain the unit and a default value.
- **Provider-specific fields** (`reasoning_effort`, Ollama
  `think: false`): explain which providers honour it and what the
  trade-offs are.
- **Settings that interact** (per-segment retry vs provider retry,
  reasoning effort vs Ollama `think`): cross-link the related field
  in plain prose.
- **Toggles whose default surprised someone** ("we default this off
  because…"): bake the rationale into the tooltip so curators don't
  have to re-discover it from the changelog.

## Skip it for

- Trivial text inputs whose label is self-describing (project name,
  language slugs).
- Internal / dev-only screens (`?mock=1` debug pages).
- Errors / inline validation messages — those are *always* visible,
  not gated on hover.

## Building block — `FieldHelp`

Every form should reach for `@/components/ui/field-help` — the
shared primitive for "label + question-mark icon → tooltip". Don't
hand-roll the pattern with bare Radix tooltips per form; consistency
matters here.

```tsx
import { FieldHelp } from "@/components/ui/field-help";

<FieldHelp
  htmlFor="num_ctx"
  label="Context window (num_ctx)"
  help={
    <>
      <p>
        Tokens loaded into context per request. Ollama default is{" "}
        <code>2048</code>; bump to <code>8192</code> for chapter-sized
        prompts.
      </p>
      <p className="mt-2">
        Doubling the window roughly doubles memory cost; if Ollama
        OOMs, drop back to 4096.
      </p>
    </>
  }
/>
<Input id="num_ctx" type="number" placeholder="2048" … />
```

## Accessibility contract

`FieldHelp` is wired so:

- The visible `<label htmlFor>` is the input's accessible name.
- The help icon has its own distinct aria-label (`Show help: <label>`)
  so `getByLabelText(/<label>/)` in tests still uniquely returns the
  input, not the help button.
- The tooltip is keyboard-reachable: tabbing to the help button opens
  it; the tooltip body uses Radix and respects screen-reader output.

## Tooltip prose conventions

- One topic, one short paragraph; up to two paragraphs separated by
  `<p className="mt-2">`.
- Inline `<code>` for default values, units, and field references
  (e.g. `<code>num_ctx</code>`, `<code>2048</code>`).
- Mention the **default**, the **unit**, and one practical
  recommendation — not three.
- Cross-link interacting fields in plain English (`see Settings → LLM →
  Reasoning effort`), don't try to render Settings-route paths in
  pseudo-breadcrumbs.

## Don't

- Don't put help-icon tooltips on read-only display values — those
  belong inline (e.g. a footnote or a disclosure card).
- Don't use a help tooltip as a workaround for a confusing field
  name. Rename the field if the tooltip starts with "actually this is
  named X for legacy reasons…".
- Don't bury validation errors inside a help tooltip; they need to be
  on-screen the moment they apply.
